
[1]tenacious

   TENA'CIOUS, a. [L. tenax, from teneo, to hold.]

   1. Holding fast, or inclined to hold fast; inclined to retain what is
   in possession; as men tenacious of their just rights. Men are usually
   tenacious of their opinions, as well as of their property.

   2. Retentive; apt to retain long what is committed to it; as a
   tenacious memory.

   3. Adhesive; apt to adhere to another substance; as oily, glutinous or
   viscous matter. Few substances are to tenacious as tar.

   4. Niggardly; close fisted.
